{"ins_1aeafb700fd80142":{"confidence":0.75,"content":"Gary's accounting-firm project is being developed in an environment where AgentMemory actively consolidates observations into structured facts. The pipeline (3+ concept-sharing observations triggering LLM consolidation, capped at 10 calls/run) suggests his primary workflow involves iterative task tracking and context recall rather than one-off interactions. This implies he benefits most from persistent, queryable project state rather than stateless request-response cycles.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:01.382Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_1aeafb700fd80142","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["user","pipeline"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_ffc2dba1dd8cf21f","lesson_7ed5125b5f113649","lesson_9956c1bfc236c94e","lesson_dc5eba3500c61f56","lesson_9fb42e546da26160","lesson_af9f0d376e7ee0e5","lesson_337dce0e47967dcc","lesson_845fb88541911f5e","lesson_245764fa674d5b5f","lesson_236c62032a4e2403","lesson_efaa3334a156b345","lesson_7c0f281a0ee663c4","lesson_ecd36ad5f36064aa","lesson_4f0e2813f5a03d87","lesson_820789d1b7fcc015","lesson_51283edb6c600dfd","lesson_ea784c127ba604ba","lesson_70aece8643d59eb1","lesson_0f7a5e6ca3a445c5","lesson_f9fa167c4f635b80","lesson_75da321aa4053444","lesson_d0c234b6e0e15135","lesson_185d5ff19f3e6751","lesson_3ce1385c90028fb9","lesson_80127a6e43077e54","lesson_3b0d8cab74741f12","lesson_d4def1e3ae349871","lesson_8dafbfe6f8ca83b5"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqq_798aea93936a","sem_mqwvjpqu_f4443d3184c6","sem_mqwvjpqy_38a18ca7f3a0"],"tags":["user","pipeline"],"title":"User workflow centers on LLM-backed memory consolidation for project context","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:01.382Z"},"ins_91eec0c453e86f78":{"confidence":0.65,"content":"Gary manually set up the Anthropic API key in ~/.agentmemory/.env, indicating intentional opt-in to LLM-powered features. Combined with the lessons learned pattern (low confidence items describing strict gating: \"wait for user approval before implementation,\" \"don't auto-invoke\"), this suggests he values *controlled automation* ŌĆö features that trigger only when explicitly authorized, not defaults that assume consent.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:01.384Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_91eec0c453e86f78","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["user","pipeline"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_ffc2dba1dd8cf21f","lesson_7ed5125b5f113649","lesson_9956c1bfc236c94e","lesson_dc5eba3500c61f56","lesson_9fb42e546da26160","lesson_af9f0d376e7ee0e5","lesson_337dce0e47967dcc","lesson_845fb88541911f5e","lesson_245764fa674d5b5f","lesson_236c62032a4e2403","lesson_efaa3334a156b345","lesson_7c0f281a0ee663c4","lesson_ecd36ad5f36064aa","lesson_4f0e2813f5a03d87","lesson_820789d1b7fcc015","lesson_51283edb6c600dfd","lesson_ea784c127ba604ba","lesson_70aece8643d59eb1","lesson_0f7a5e6ca3a445c5","lesson_f9fa167c4f635b80","lesson_75da321aa4053444","lesson_d0c234b6e0e15135","lesson_185d5ff19f3e6751","lesson_3ce1385c90028fb9","lesson_80127a6e43077e54","lesson_3b0d8cab74741f12","lesson_d4def1e3ae349871","lesson_8dafbfe6f8ca83b5"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqq_798aea93936a","sem_mqwvjpqu_f4443d3184c6","sem_mqwvjpqy_38a18ca7f3a0"],"tags":["user","pipeline"],"title":"User explicitly configured API credentials to enable automation","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:01.384Z"},"ins_f448df8c70ce3b7f":{"confidence":0.6,"content":"The majority of low-confidence \"lessons\" describe actions to *suppress* (don't implement without approval, don't amend commits, don't skip hooks, don't hard-delete) rather than actions to perform. This pattern indicates Gary's past experience likely involved surprises or irreversible changes triggered too eagerly. The system should default to *presenting proposals and waiting for confirmation* rather than autonomously executing changes.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:01.386Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_f448df8c70ce3b7f","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["user","pipeline"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_ffc2dba1dd8cf21f","lesson_7ed5125b5f113649","lesson_9956c1bfc236c94e","lesson_dc5eba3500c61f56","lesson_9fb42e546da26160","lesson_af9f0d376e7ee0e5","lesson_337dce0e47967dcc","lesson_845fb88541911f5e","lesson_245764fa674d5b5f","lesson_236c62032a4e2403","lesson_efaa3334a156b345","lesson_7c0f281a0ee663c4","lesson_ecd36ad5f36064aa","lesson_4f0e2813f5a03d87","lesson_820789d1b7fcc015","lesson_51283edb6c600dfd","lesson_ea784c127ba604ba","lesson_70aece8643d59eb1","lesson_0f7a5e6ca3a445c5","lesson_f9fa167c4f635b80","lesson_75da321aa4053444","lesson_d0c234b6e0e15135","lesson_185d5ff19f3e6751","lesson_3ce1385c90028fb9","lesson_80127a6e43077e54","lesson_3b0d8cab74741f12","lesson_d4def1e3ae349871","lesson_8dafbfe6f8ca83b5"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqq_798aea93936a","sem_mqwvjpqu_f4443d3184c6","sem_mqwvjpqy_38a18ca7f3a0"],"tags":["user","pipeline"],"title":"Lessons cluster around preventing unintended action execution","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:01.386Z"},"ins_928e4235da7249c2":{"confidence":0.85,"content":"Effective consolidationŌĆöwhether UI navigation, memory systems, or implementationŌĆöbenefits from explicit thresholds (3+ observations, capped LLM calls) and phased rollout (evaluation groups). This prevents premature aggregation and manages resource costs while ensuring quality before full integration.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:06.043Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_928e4235da7249c2","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["into","consolidation"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_8c29b448e40b8ac4","lesson_6db40b595ede1724"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqs_902d57c9b270","sem_mqwvjpqu_f4443d3184c6","sem_mqwvjpqw_f63355b1d13a","sem_mqwvjpqy_38a18ca7f3a0"],"tags":["into","consolidation"],"title":"Consolidation requires staged gating with resource constraints","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:06.043Z"},"ins_d4e6d037ed1f28ea":{"confidence":0.8,"content":"The AgentMemory architecture separates lightweight local indexing (observations) from expensive LLM-backed consolidation (durable memories), mirroring how UI consolidation required staging backend/frontend/testing separately. This decoupling allows you to accumulate data cheaply before investing in expensive integration work.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:06.045Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_d4e6d037ed1f28ea","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["into","consolidation"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_8c29b448e40b8ac4","lesson_6db40b595ede1724"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqs_902d57c9b270","sem_mqwvjpqu_f4443d3184c6","sem_mqwvjpqw_f63355b1d13a","sem_mqwvjpqy_38a18ca7f3a0"],"tags":["into","consolidation"],"title":"Separation of storage and processing enables flexible consolidation","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:06.045Z"},"ins_a65eaf225ebf1d0c":{"confidence":0.75,"content":"Both the lesson about rushing implementation and the phased evaluation groups point to a core principle: consolidation moves faster than adoption. Build breathing room into timelinesŌĆölet systems and teams stabilize after merging before the next consolidation wave.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:06.046Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_a65eaf225ebf1d0c","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["into","consolidation"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_8c29b448e40b8ac4","lesson_6db40b595ede1724"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqs_902d57c9b270","sem_mqwvjpqu_f4443d3184c6","sem_mqwvjpqw_f63355b1d13a","sem_mqwvjpqy_38a18ca7f3a0"],"tags":["into","consolidation"],"title":"Consolidation velocity must match stakeholder readiness","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:06.046Z"},"ins_c5812af0199aaa25":{"confidence":0.7,"content":"The AgentMemory pipeline was blocked until the Anthropic API key was configured; the OpenSpec change required backend readiness. Identify and surface dependency chains earlyŌĆöconsolidation can't proceed without all pieces, making dependency clarity more important than speed.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:06.047Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_c5812af0199aaa25","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["into","consolidation"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_8c29b448e40b8ac4","lesson_6db40b595ede1724"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqs_902d57c9b270","sem_mqwvjpqu_f4443d3184c6","sem_mqwvjpqw_f63355b1d13a","sem_mqwvjpqy_38a18ca7f3a0"],"tags":["into","consolidation"],"title":"External dependencies are consolidation bottlenecks","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:06.047Z"},"ins_cb5abc906a78aaba":{"confidence":0.75,"content":"Derived query fields like activeEngagementStatus computed server-side should never be assumed non-null in client code; defensive null checks prevent silent failures when computation returns unexpected empty states, especially critical for status-dependent UI logic.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:09.711Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_cb5abc906a78aaba","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["includes","engagement","status"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_9a9443ad8fc53f15","lesson_966360d1913aa6b7","lesson_0b617ed8f1a89695","lesson_a294122a71da6d98"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqt_738214f716a5","sem_mqwvjpqt_a410b90fc68d","sem_mqwvjpqx_b8799e631fdf"],"tags":["includes","engagement","status"],"title":"Server-computed status fields require explicit null safety","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:09.711Z"},"ins_b0e46fdf37e78dab":{"confidence":0.7,"content":"Engagement status transitions (START ŌåÆ IN_PROCESSING ŌåÆ PENDING_CLIENT_REVIEW ŌåÆ SUBMIT_TO_CRA/GOVERNMENT ŌåÆ COMPLETED) define hard validation gates; bypassing status checks (e.g., REVIEWED validation) creates inconsistency that compounds downstreamŌĆöenforce these at assignment time, not retroactively.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:09.711Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_b0e46fdf37e78dab","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["includes","engagement","status"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_9a9443ad8fc53f15","lesson_966360d1913aa6b7","lesson_0b617ed8f1a89695","lesson_a294122a71da6d98"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqt_738214f716a5","sem_mqwvjpqt_a410b90fc68d","sem_mqwvjpqx_b8799e631fdf"],"tags":["includes","engagement","status"],"title":"Status lifecycle checkpoints are enforcement boundaries","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:09.711Z"},"ins_9299c98cff8a099b":{"confidence":0.65,"content":"Rate-limit and authentication errors in login flows (HttpErrorResponse status codes with localized messages) parallel engagement status lifecycle concerns; consistent error classification and user-facing messaging across protocol and domain layers reduces confusion about what state the system actually entered.","createdAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:09.712Z","decayRate":0.05,"id":"ins_9299c98cff8a099b","reinforcements":0,"sourceConceptCluster":["includes","engagement","status"],"sourceCrystalIds":[],"sourceLessonIds":["lesson_9a9443ad8fc53f15","lesson_966360d1913aa6b7","lesson_0b617ed8f1a89695","lesson_a294122a71da6d98"],"sourceMemoryIds":["sem_mqwvjpqt_738214f716a5","sem_mqwvjpqt_a410b90fc68d","sem_mqwvjpqx_b8799e631fdf"],"tags":["includes","engagement","status"],"title":"HTTP error handling should mirror domain status semantics","updatedAt":"2026-06-27T21:31:09.712Z"}}␀␀é»␀␀<į  